[
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q039",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "programming",
    "subtopic": "cpp-loops",
    "stem": "What is the output of the following (C++ Code)?",
    "stemCode": "int n;\nfor (n = 5; n > 0; n--) {\n     cout << n;\n     if (n == 3)\n        break;\n}",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "543",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "54",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "54321",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "543210",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 39
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "85d9c8a747442a62353c71195f319c4f58cab8fe",
    "explanation": "The loop prints n, then checks the break. n=5 prints 5, n=4 prints 4, n=3 prints 3 and then hits the break, so output is 543. The trap is the ordering: because cout runs before the if, the 3 is printed before the loop exits, so answer B (54) is wrong."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q040",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "arp",
    "stem": "The address resolution Protocol (ARP) is used to _________________ .",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Find the IP address corresponding to MAC address.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Find the port address corresponding to an IP address.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Find the MAC address corresponding to an IP address.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Find the IP address from the DNS.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 40
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "2683a41e7c710c744b81db3384770312808d65cc",
    "explanation": "ARP takes a known IP address and resolves it to the MAC address of the host on the local link, so frames can actually be addressed at layer 2. The trap is option A, which is the reverse mapping (MAC to IP), the job of RARP; DNS resolves names to IPs, not addresses to MACs."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q041",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "mac-address",
    "stem": "What is the size of the MAC address?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "16-bits.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "32-bits.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "48-bits.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "64-bits.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 41
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "cbde35a5a38ca14d8a1355add3123f5548cb2b54",
    "explanation": "An IEEE 802 MAC address (EUI-48) is 6 bytes = 48 bits, written as six hex pairs such as 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E. 32 bits is the trap, because that is the size of an IPv4 address."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q042",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "osi-layers",
    "stem": "Mac address is an Example of _______________ .",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "Transport Layer.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "Data Link Layer.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "Application Layer.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Physical Layer.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 42
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "58645d5b9f90d1babcd1da8a7012f348fb9c9dcd",
    "explanation": "MAC stands for Media Access Control, which is the lower sublayer of OSI layer 2, the Data Link layer. The Physical layer is the trap: it deals with bits, voltages and cabling and has no notion of addressing at all."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q043",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "atm",
    "stem": "Packet length in ATM Network?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "40 Bytes.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "50 Bytes.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "53 Bytes.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "Variable Length.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 43
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "e8415520e0a157225f85d7a2ed94045d2d7d8fb8",
    "explanation": "ATM uses a fixed-size cell of 53 bytes: a 5-byte header plus a 48-byte payload. The fixed length is the whole point of ATM, since it makes switching and delay predictable, so 'variable length' is the trap for anyone thinking of IP packets."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q044",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "data-structures-algorithms",
    "subtopic": "binary-search-tree",
    "stem": "A Binary Tree is considered a Binary Search Tree if:",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "The key in each node is greater than all keys stored in the left sub-tree, and smaller than all keys in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "The key in each node is smaller than all keys stored in the left sub-tree, and greater than all keys in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "The key in a parent node is greater than all keys of its children nodes.",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "For each node, the number of nodes in left sub-tree is equal to the number of nodes in the right sub-tree.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 44
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "ca1c4298537bf5a57b095e94a16a540c2bc4cf98",
    "explanation": "The BST invariant is that for every node, all keys in its left subtree are smaller and all keys in its right subtree are larger, which is option A and is what makes an in-order traversal come out sorted. Option B inverts the ordering, C describes a max-heap, and D describes a balanced (not a search) tree; a BST need not be balanced."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q045",
    "type": "true_false",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "ram",
    "stem": "RAM cell is associated with identifier called address.",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "True.",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "False.",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "source": {
      "file": "[CE] questions.pdf",
      "exam": "K-Companies",
      "year": 2016,
      "tier": "gold",
      "originalNumber": 45
    },
    "keyProvenance": "answer_page",
    "flags": [],
    "keyVerified": true,
    "needsReview": false,
    "dedupeHash": "9d8d1b0ae8fe5585d9da62b84205bd9e55a89847",
    "explanation": "True. Memory is organised as cells, each with a unique numeric address, and it is precisely this addressability that lets the CPU reach any cell directly in constant time, which is what 'random access' means."
  },
  {
    "id": "ce2016-q046",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "hardware-memory",
    "subtopic": "ram",
